print("Solution 3.f: Identification of Skewness:The skewness of the given data columns can be identfied as:\n1. The frequency curve of the distribution is not a symmetric bell shaped curve but stretched more to one side than to the other.\n2. The values of mean (M), median (Md) and mode (Mo) fall at different points i.e they dont coincide.\n3. Quartiles Q1 and Q3 are not equidistant from the median.\n4. The corresponding pairs of deciles and percentiles are not equidistant from the median.")

Solution 3.f: Identification of Skewness:The skewness of the given data columns can be identfied as:
1. The frequency curve of the distribution is not a symmetric bell shaped curve but stretched more to one side than to the other.
2. The values of mean (M), median (Md) and mode (Mo) fall at different points i.e they dont coincide.
3. Quartiles Q1 and Q3 are not equidistant from the median.
4. The corresponding pairs of deciles and percentiles are not equidistant from the median.
In [39]:
print("Measurement of skewness- The first coefficient of skewness as defined by Karl Pearson is (mean-mode)/standard deviation.\nSkewness will be positive if mean > mode and negative if mean < mode. There is no limit to this measure in theory and this is a slight drawback. But in practice the value given by this formula is rarely very high and its value usually lies between -1 and +1.")

Measurement of skewness- The first coefficient of skewness as defined by Karl Pearson is (mean-mode)/standard deviation.
Skewness will be positive if mean > mode and negative if mean < mode. There is no limit to this measure in theory and this is a slight drawback. But in practice the value given by this formula is rarely very high and its value usually lies between -1 and +1.

In [74]:
print("Solution 4.a: The data has been splitted in to smokers and non smokers' charges. \nWe will try to check whether the mean of charges for these two data sets now are equal.\nThe count of observations for smokers(274) and non smokers(1064) are not equal, but we will assume the variance is same. \nFor testing we will be deploying a hypothesis testing with a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.\nWe will test whether we can accept or fail to accept the null hypothesis using a Ttest for independant group.\nWe will be testing the nul hypothesis with a confidence level of 95%.\nThis will be a 2 tailed test as we are not testing that the given means are more or less of each other, but just whether they are equal or not.\nThe hypotheses are defined as below:\n   Ho = The charges as leveid upon insurance by smokers and non smokers are same (Mu_smoker = Mu_nsmoker).\n   Ha = The charges as leveid upon insurance by smokers and non smokers are not same (Mu_smoker != Mu_nsmoker).")

Solution 4.a: The data has been splitted in to smokers and non smokers' charges. 
We will try to check whether the mean of charges for these two data sets now are equal.
The count of observations for smokers(274) and non smokers(1064) are not equal, but we will assume the variance is same. 
For testing we will be deploying a hypothesis testing with a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.
We will test whether we can accept or fail to accept the null hypothesis using a Ttest for independant group.
We will be testing the nul hypothesis with a confidence level of 95%.
This will be a 2 tailed test as we are not testing that the given means are more or less of each other, but just whether they are equal or not.
The hypotheses are defined as below:
   Ho = The charges as leveid upon insurance by smokers and non smokers are same (Mu_smoker = Mu_nsmoker).
   Ha = The charges as leveid upon insurance by smokers and non smokers are not same (Mu_smoker != Mu_nsmoker).
In [75]:
t_critical = 1.677 #(corresponding to 95% confidence)
print("t_critical=",1.677)
Ns = 274
Nns= 1064
ds = Ns-1
dns= Nns-1
df = ds+dns
ss=np.std(smoker_ch['charges'],ddof = 1)
sns = np.std(nsmoker_ch['charges'],ddof =1)
S_bar = np.mean(smoker_ch['charges'])
Ns_bar = np.mean(nsmoker_ch['charges'])

sp = np.sqrt((ds*ss**2+ dns*sns**2)/df)
se = sp*np.sqrt(1/Ns + 1/Nns)
t = (S_bar - Ns_bar)/(se)
print("t-statistic_manual",t)

t_statistic_scipy, p_value = ttest_ind(smoker_ch['charges'],nsmoker_ch['charges'])
print("t_statistic_scipy=", t_statistic_scipy, p_value)

t_critical= 1.677
t-statistic_manual 46.66492117272374
t_statistic_scipy= 46.664921172723716 8.271435842177219e-283
In [76]:
print("Comparing the t statistic (we have calculated in both ways, manually as well as using scipy) with the t_critical, we can say the t_statitic is much more than the t critical and we can reject the null hypothesis.\n Seeing the p value which is very much less than the 0.05, we can say that withh 95% confidence level we can reject the null hypothesis, Ho.\n Hence, we can conclude that the charges levied by the smokers on insurance company is not equal to the charges levied by non smokers on insurance company.")

Comparing the t statistic (we have calculated in both ways, manually as well as using scipy) with the t_critical, we can say the t_statitic is much more than the t critical and we can reject the null hypothesis.
 Seeing the p value which is very much less than the 0.05, we can say that withh 95% confidence level we can reject the null hypothesis, Ho.
 Hence, we can conclude that the charges levied by the smokers on insurance company is not equal to the charges levied by non smokers on insurance company.

Solution 4.b: The data has been splitted in to male and female's bmi. 
We will try to check whether the mean of bmi for these two data sets now are equal.
The count of observations for male(676) and female(662) are not equal, but we will assume the variance is same. 
For testing we will be deploying a hypothesis testing with a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.
We will test whether we can accept or fail to accept the null hypothesis using a Ttest for independant group.
We will be testing the nul hypothesis with a confidence level of 95%.
This will be a 2 tailed test as we are not testing that the given means are more or less of each other, but just whether they are equal or not.
The hypotheses are defined as below:
   Ho = The bmi of male and female in the data set provided are same (Mu_male = Mu_female).
   Ha = The bmi of male and female in the data set provided are not same (Mu_male != Mu_female).
In [81]:
t_critical = 1.677 #(corresponding to 95% confidence)
print("t_critical=",1.677)
Nm = 676
Nf= 662
dm = Nm-1
df= Nf-1
dfm = dm+df
sm = np.std(bmi_m['bmi'],ddof = 1)
sf = np.std(bmi_f['bmi'],ddof = 1)
M_bar = np.mean(bmi_m['bmi'])
F_bar = np.mean(bmi_f['bmi'])

sp = np.sqrt((dm*sm**2+ df*sf**2)/dfm)
se = sp*np.sqrt(1/Nm + 1/Nf)
t = (M_bar - F_bar)/(se)
print("t-statistic_manual",t)

t_statistic_scipy, p_value = ttest_ind(bmi_m['bmi'],bmi_f['bmi'])

print("Solution 4.c: The data has been splitted in to male and female's proportion of smokers. \nWe will try to check whether the proportions for these two data sets are equal or not.\nFor testing we will be deploying a hypothesis testing with a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.\nThe proportions are compared by representing in proxies of 0 and 1 and then taking the average of 1s in the data as proportion and compare.\nSince a large number of data(mean of data) is involved CLT will be used.\nWe will test whether we can accept or fail to accept the null hypothesis using a proportons Z test for independant groups.\nWe will be testing the nul hypothesis with a confidence level of 95%.\nThis will be a 2 tailed test as we are not testing that the given proportions are more or less of each other, but just whether they are equal or not.\nThe hypotheses are defined as below:\n   Ho = The proportions of smokers in male and female in the data set provided are same (P_sm_male = P_sm_female).\n   Ha = The proportions of smokers in male and female in the data set provided are not same (P_sm_male != P_sm_female).")

Solution 4.c: The data has been splitted in to male and female's proportion of smokers. 
We will try to check whether the proportions for these two data sets are equal or not.
For testing we will be deploying a hypothesis testing with a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis.
The proportions are compared by representing in proxies of 0 and 1 and then taking the average of 1s in the data as proportion and compare.
Since a large number of data(mean of data) is involved CLT will be used.
We will test whether we can accept or fail to accept the null hypothesis using a proportons Z test for independant groups.
We will be testing the nul hypothesis with a confidence level of 95%.
This will be a 2 tailed test as we are not testing that the given proportions are more or less of each other, but just whether they are equal or not.
The hypotheses are defined as below:
   Ho = The proportions of smokers in male and female in the data set provided are same (P_sm_male = P_sm_female).
   Ha = The proportions of smokers in male and female in the data set provided are not same (P_sm_male != P_sm_female).
